        What Does a Solicitor Do When You Sell Your Property in Brisbane?
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Your solicitor handles much more than the contract review. Here's what they actually do throughout a Brisbane property sale, what it costs, and the issues they most commonly catch before settlement.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most Brisbane sellers engage a solicitor or conveyancer relatively late in the process, sometimes only after a contract has been signed. This is usually too late. Your legal representative plays an important role not just at settlement but throughout the campaign, and engaging them early, ideally before you sign your agency agreement, gives them the opportunity to identify issues while there is still time to address them.</p>

      <p>What a solicitor does on a property sale is more extensive than many sellers realise. Understanding their role gives you a clearer picture of the process from contract to settlement and helps you get more value from the legal work you are paying for.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The specific tasks a seller's solicitor handles</h2>
      <p>Before the contract is signed, your solicitor should review the proposed terms of sale, including any special conditions your agent has negotiated, and advise on any clauses that are unfavourable or unusual. In Queensland, the standard REIQ contract is widely used, but the special conditions section varies significantly from sale to sale and can contain terms that have real financial consequences for the seller. A solicitor who reviews the contract before signing, rather than after, is in a position to catch issues while they can still be addressed.</p>

      <p>Once the contract is executed, the solicitor's work includes conducting a title search to verify clear ownership and identify any encumbrances, easements, caveats or mortgages registered against the property. They will liaise with your mortgage lender to coordinate the discharge of any existing mortgage, which must be completed before or at settlement. In Brisbane, this discharge process can take several weeks if the lender is slow to respond, and experienced solicitors manage this timeline proactively to avoid settlement delays.</p>

      <p>The solicitor prepares the transfer documentation: the Form 1 Transfer, which is the document that legally transfers ownership of the property from you to the buyer. This document is lodged with the Queensland Titles Registry at settlement. They also prepare the settlement figures, including the adjustment of rates, water and body corporate levies between seller and buyer as at the settlement date. These adjustments ensure that each party pays only for the period during which they owned the property.</p>

      <p>At settlement itself, the solicitor attends on your behalf (in Queensland, electronic settlement via PEXA is now the standard for most residential transactions), coordinates the simultaneous exchange of funds and transfer documentation with the buyer's solicitor, and confirms completion. After settlement, they notify the relevant authorities and confirm that the discharge of mortgage has been registered.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Solicitor versus conveyancer: which do you need?</h2>
      <p>Both solicitors and licensed conveyancers can handle residential property transactions in Queensland. The practical distinction comes down to complexity. A licensed conveyancer is trained specifically in property transactions and can competently handle the majority of standard residential sales. A solicitor has broader legal training and can advise on matters beyond the conveyancing itself: estate planning considerations, family law implications of the sale, tax advice, contract disputes or issues that arise during the campaign that have legal dimensions beyond the conveyancing scope.</p>

      <p>For a straightforward sale with a clean title, no complications around ownership structure, and a cooperative buyer, a conveyancer is usually adequate and may be less expensive. For a sale involving complex ownership arrangements (tenants in common, deceased estates, company or trust ownership), known title issues, or a buyer who is likely to be difficult, a solicitor's broader expertise is worth having. When in doubt, engage a solicitor. The difference in cost is modest relative to the transaction value and the potential cost of a problem that falls outside a conveyancer's scope to resolve.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Typical costs for seller's legal work in Brisbane</h2>
      <p>Legal costs for a residential property sale in Brisbane typically fall in the range of $1,200 to $2,500 for a standard transaction, including disbursements. The primary variables are the complexity of the title, the firm's fee structure (fixed fee versus hourly rate), and whether any issues arise during the conveyancing process that require additional work.</p>

      <p>Fixed-fee arrangements are common and predictable, which most sellers prefer. When comparing quotes, confirm what is included in the fixed fee and what is treated as an additional charge. Mortgage discharge fees, title search fees and PEXA fees are sometimes bundled and sometimes charged separately. A quote of $900 that excludes these disbursements may cost more in total than a quote of $1,500 that includes everything.</p>

      <p>If the transaction becomes complicated, for example if the buyer exercises a finance clause extension, if a caveat needs to be removed, or if the building and pest inspection throws up a negotiation over remediation, the legal costs will increase. This is normal and reflects additional work performed. The risk of unforeseen complexity is one reason to engage a firm with a transparent fee escalation policy rather than one that gives you a fixed quote and then surprises you with additions at the end.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the solicitor and agent work together during the campaign</h2>
      <p>The relationship between your agent and your solicitor is a working one throughout the campaign, not just at settlement. Your agent will need the solicitor's contact details to provide to buyers' solicitors for contract exchange. Once a contract is executed, the agent typically sends a copy to the solicitor immediately and the two parties then coordinate on the timeline and any conditions.</p>

      <p>If a buyer requests an extension to a finance clause, the agent will manage the negotiation with the buyer but the formal extension is often documented as a contract variation and the solicitor should be informed. If a buyer exercises their right to terminate under a building and pest clause, the agent manages the communication and the solicitor handles the formal termination process and the return of deposit.</p>

      <p>A seller who keeps their solicitor and agent informed of each other and who facilitates communication between the two parties will generally have a smoother transaction than one who treats them as separate silos. Both parties are working toward the same outcome: a completed settlement on the agreed date, on the agreed terms.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common issues solicitors identify that delay or derail settlements</h2>
      <p>Experienced solicitors see the same issues repeat across transactions. Title encumbrances are among the most common: easements, covenants or caveats that appear on the title search and that the seller was unaware of or had forgotten about. Some are benign and easily explained to the buyer. Others require formal steps to remove and can take weeks or months, which may be incompatible with the agreed settlement date.</p>

      <p>Mortgage discharge delays are a frequent cause of settlement extensions. Lenders sometimes take longer than anticipated to process discharge requests, particularly if documentation is incomplete or if the loan account has irregularities. Engaging your solicitor early and asking them to initiate the discharge process as soon as the contract is unconditional is the most effective way to reduce this risk.</p>

      <p>Outstanding rates or water charges can cause complications if they are not identified early in the conveyancing process. Brisbane City Council charges, body corporate levies and water utilities all need to be adjusted at settlement, and any arrears must be cleared. A solicitor who identifies outstanding charges early gives the seller time to address them before they become a settlement issue.</p>

      <p>Ownership structure irregularities are less common but more serious when they occur. If the property is owned by a deceased person, a company that has been deregistered, or in a structure that does not match what is recorded on the title, the conveyancing process will need to resolve the discrepancy before transfer can proceed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should bring to the first meeting</h2>
      <p>The more information you give your solicitor at the first meeting, the more efficiently they can do their job. Bring your title documents if you have them, the contract of sale (or the proposed special conditions if the contract is not yet signed), your mortgage details including your lender's name and loan account number, and any relevant documents relating to the property: easement agreements, body corporate information, tenancy agreements if the property is tenanted, and any building approval certificates for improvements you have made.</p>

      <p>If you are aware of any issues with the property, disclose them to your solicitor at the outset. Issues that you know about and do not disclose can create legal liability and are almost always better addressed proactively than discovered by the buyer during the due diligence process.</p>

